Its foreign minister Mevlut Cavusoglu says the new round of negotiations to be held in Kazakh capital Astana is at risk. JOHANNESBURG - Turkey has accused the Syrian government of violating a fragile ceasefire.Its foreign minister Mevlut Cavusoglu says the new round of negotiations to be held in Kazakh capital Astana is at risk. Last week's Russian-Turkish brokered ceasefire has brought calm to large parts of Syria but has been threatened by ongoing fighting. Turkey has urged the Syrian regime and its supporters to end their violations of the truce saying they are endangering the planned talks.Turkey is working with Russia on the question of sanctions for those who violate the ceasefire deal, which was brokered by Ankara and Moscow, Cavusoglu said in a televised interview with the state-run Anadolu news agency.He warned that peace negotiations being prepared by Moscow in the Kazakh capital, Astana, could fail if increased ceasefire violations are not halted.Additional reporting by Reuters